{"title_page": "Kimberly Drew", "text_new": "{{Like resume|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Kimberly Drew\n| image = File:MoMA edit a thon 104 .jpg\n| alt = https://www.contemporary.org/img/headshot/drew.jpg \n| caption =Kimberly Drew speaking at Art+Feminism at MoMA\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =  {{birth year and age|1990}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| alma_mater = [[Smith College]]\n| occupation = Curator<br />\nblogger<br />\nFormer [[social media]] manager for the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n| years_active = 2011\u2013\n| known_for = @MuseumMammy [[Instagram]] account<br />\nBlack Contemporary Art blog on [[Tumblr]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Kimberly Drew''' (born 1990)<ref name=\"Broadly-Feature-2016\" /> is a [[curator]] of \"black art and experiences\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/07/style/kimberly-drew-black-contemporary-art.html|title=Kimberly Drew Is a Curator of Black Art and Experiences|last=Oswaks|first=Molly|date=2018-12-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, as well as the creator of the popular [[Tumblr]] blog \"Black Contemporary Art\".<ref name=\"NYorker-ArtofProtest-2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/07/25/kimberly-drews-art-of-protest|title=Art of Protest|last1=Tammy Kim|first1=E.|date=July 25, 2016|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-Curation-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2015/11/30/kimberly-drews-curation-brings-black-artists-to-the-forefront/|title=Kimberly Drew's curation brings black artists to the forefront|last1=WITW Staff|date=November 30, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>. She previously held the position of [[social media]] manager for the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]. Drew supplements the Tumblr with accounts on Facebook, Twitter, and [[Instagram]], which she uses to champion black artists and the cause of [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref name=\"NYorker-ArtofProtest-2016\" /><ref name=\"LennyLetter-Interview-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lennyletter.com/culture/interviews/a173/meet-the-instagram-star-elevating-black-contemporary-art/|title=The Lenny Interview: Kimberly Drew, aka @MuseumMammy|date=November 27, 2015|work=[[Lenny Letter]]|access-date=July 27, 2017|last1=St. F\u00e9lix|first1=Doreen}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDrew grew up in [[Orange, New Jersey|Orange]], New Jersey,<ref name=\"Smith-SAE-Spotlight-2016\">{{cite news|url=http://alumnae.smith.edu/spotlight/shaking-the-canon/|title=Alumnae Spotlight. Shaking the Canon: Internet tastemakers Kimberly Drew '12 brings overrdue attention to black contemporary art and artists|date=Fall 2016|work=Smith Alumnae Quarterly|access-date=July 27, 2017|publisher=[[Smith College]], Office of Alumnae Relations|last1=Simpson|first1=April}}</ref> and currently lives in [[Brooklyn]], New York City.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bkmag.com/2017/03/13/brooklyn-100-influencer-kimberly-drew-metropolitan-museum-art/|title=Brooklyn 100 Influencer: Kimberly Drew, MET Museum|last=Miller|first=Rachel|date=March 13, 2017|website=Brooklyn Magazine|access-date=2017-04-11}}</ref>\n\nGrowing up, she was raised in a family of artists.<ref name=\"SSENSE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ssense.com/en-us/editorial/culture/kimberly-rose-drew|title=Kimberly Rose Drew on the Limits of Utopia|last=SSENSE|date=November 21, 2017|work=ssense|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en-us}}</ref> In 2008, Drew graduated from the [[boarding school]] [[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]] in [[Middletown, Rhode Island|Middletown]], Rhode Island.<ref name=StGeorges-NewsRoundup-2016>{{cite news|title=News Roundup: Kimberly Drew \u201908|url=http://www.stgeorges.edu/cf_news/view.cfm?newsid=226|work=[[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]]|date=July 22, 2016}}</ref> During her [[Sophomore|second year]] at [[Smith College]], Drew had an [[internship]] at [[Studio Museum in Harlem]] with [[Thelma Golden]], which influenced her later choice of concentration.<ref name=LennyLetter-Interview-2015 /> She said the experience of working in a museum informed her career path. In 2012, Drew graduated from [[Smith College]] with a B.A. in [[Art history]] and [[Africana studies]], and a concentration in [[Museology|Museum Studies]].<ref name=Smith-SAE-Spotlight-2016 />\n\n== Career ==\nIn March 2011, Drew started the [[Tumblr]] blog called \"Black Contemporary Art\" while still in college.<ref name=Smith-SAE-Spotlight-2016 /> When she began \"Black Contemporary Art,\" Drew and others would write posts about black artists who were featured on museum websites but not on Tumblr so that they \"were part of a recorded history.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/04/18/kimberly-drew-museummammy|title=Meet The Social Media Star Whose Taste The Art World Follows|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en}}</ref> As such, she aimed to help \"more marginalized people enter institutions, learn the rules, and shatter and restructure them.\"<ref name=\"Miller\"/>\n\nIn July 2015, Drew was hired as the Associate Online Community Producer at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York City.<ref name=\"Met-ArtOfSocialMedia-2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/blogs/teen-blog/2016/the-art-of-social-media|title=The Art of Social Media with Kimberly Drew|date=August 9, 2016|work=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|access-date=July 27, 2017|last1=Ambar}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Drew was invited to curate the [[White House]]'s Instagram account during the 2016 South by South Lawn festival.<ref name=\"Broadly-Feature-2016\">{{cite news|url=https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/kimberly-drew-museum-mammy-interview|title=Curator Kimberly Drew on Black Art, Social Media, and Taking Selfies in Museums|date=November 25, 2016|work=Broadly|access-date=July 27, 2017|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|last1=Agrawal|first1=Nadya}}</ref><ref name=ArtNews-SouthSouthLawn-2016>{{cite news|last1=Russeth|first1=Andrew|title=The Met's Social Medial Manager, Kimberly Drew, is on the White House's Instagram Account Today|url=http://www.artnews.com/2016/10/03/the-mets-social-media-manager-kimberly-drew-is-on-the-white-houses-instagram-account-today/|work=[[ARTnews]]|date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, Drew worked with the [[Aperture Foundation]] as a social media consultant.<ref name=\"Met-ArtOfSocialMedia-2016\" /><ref name=\"NYorker-ArtofProtest-2016\" /> [[Artsy (website)|Artsy]] included her in a roundup of art-world leaders who are \"advancing [[racial equality]] in the art world.\"\n\nIn July of 2016, Drew, along with writers Taylor Renee Aldridge and Jessica Lynne and art historian Jessica Bell Brown, organized a project called Black Art Incubator,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-mets-kimberly-drew-tells-us-the-art-world-she-wants-to-see-700547|title=Where the Met's Kimberly Drew Sees the Art World in 10 Years {{!}} artnet News|date=October 17, 2016|work=artnet News|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en-US}}</ref> a two-month long program of book exchanges, art [[critique]]s, and [[panel discussion]]s which aimed to '\u2019prioritize Black [[subjectivity]] through the use of [[social sculpture]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.recessart.org/blackartincubator/|title=BLACK ART INCUBATOR {{!}} Recess|website=www.recessart.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> \n\nDrew is currently co-authoring a book with [[Jenna Wortham]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/projects/13528952/american-women-in-art-female-artists-lorna-simpson/|title=These Women in the Arts Don't Take No for an Answer|last=Simpson|first=Koa Beck, Lorna|date=March 8, 2017|work=Vogue|access-date=2017-10-04|language=en-US}}</ref> ''The Black Futures Project,'' which will examine how creativity relates to black [[cultural identity]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/the-mets-social-media-manager-kimberly-drew-on-black-contemporary-art-public-speaking-and-more|title=This 26-Year-Old Has Already Mastered Social Media, the Met, and the Art World|last=Williamson|first=Sue|date=November 16, 2016|work=Teen Vogue|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en}}</ref> and will be published by [[Chris Jackson (publisher)|Chris Jackson]]'s One World imprint at [[Random House]] in July of 2019.<ref name=\"SSENSE\"/> Additionally, Drew will publish ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1119475558 This is What I Know About Art],'' a book for young adults'','' in June 2020 with the [[Penguin Random House|Penguin Workshop]] imprint as part of the Pocket Change Collective series<ref>https://www.teenvogue.com/story/pocket-change-collective-covers</ref>. <!--<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Black_Futures_Project.html?id=n8junAAACAAJ|title=The Black Futures Project|last=Wortham|first=Jenna|last2=Drew|first2=Kimberly|date=July 2, 2019|publisher=One World|isbn=9780399181153|language=en}}</ref>-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://blackcontemporaryart.tumblr.com Black Contemporary Art blog]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/museummammy/ @museummammy] on Instagram\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drew, Kimberly}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Smith College alumni]]\n[[Category:Women curators]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Like resume|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Kimberly Drew\n| image = File:MoMA edit a thon 104 .jpg\n| alt = https://www.contemporary.org/img/headshot/drew.jpg \n| caption =Kimberly Drew speaking at Art+Feminism at MoMA\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =  {{birth year and age|1990}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| alma_mater = [[Smith College]]\n| occupation = Curator<br />\nblogger<br />\n[[social media]] manager for the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n| years_active = 2011\u2013\n| known_for = @MuseumMammy [[Instagram]] account<br />\nBlack Contemporary Art blog on [[Tumblr]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Kimberly Drew''' (born 1990)<ref name=\"Broadly-Feature-2016\" /> is a [[curator]] of \"black art and experiences\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/07/style/kimberly-drew-black-contemporary-art.html|title=Kimberly Drew Is a Curator of Black Art and Experiences|last=Oswaks|first=Molly|date=2018-12-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, as well as the creator of the popular [[Tumblr]] blog \"Black Contemporary Art\".<ref name=\"NYorker-ArtofProtest-2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/07/25/kimberly-drews-art-of-protest|title=Art of Protest|last1=Tammy Kim|first1=E.|date=July 25, 2016|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-Curation-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2015/11/30/kimberly-drews-curation-brings-black-artists-to-the-forefront/|title=Kimberly Drew's curation brings black artists to the forefront|last1=WITW Staff|date=November 30, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>. She previously held the position of [[social media]] manager for the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]. Drew supplements the Tumblr with accounts on Facebook, Twitter, and [[Instagram]], which she uses to champion black artists and the cause of [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref name=\"NYorker-ArtofProtest-2016\" /><ref name=\"LennyLetter-Interview-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lennyletter.com/culture/interviews/a173/meet-the-instagram-star-elevating-black-contemporary-art/|title=The Lenny Interview: Kimberly Drew, aka @MuseumMammy|date=November 27, 2015|work=[[Lenny Letter]]|access-date=July 27, 2017|last1=St. F\u00e9lix|first1=Doreen}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDrew grew up in [[Orange, New Jersey|Orange]], New Jersey,<ref name=\"Smith-SAE-Spotlight-2016\">{{cite news|url=http://alumnae.smith.edu/spotlight/shaking-the-canon/|title=Alumnae Spotlight. Shaking the Canon: Internet tastemakers Kimberly Drew '12 brings overrdue attention to black contemporary art and artists|date=Fall 2016|work=Smith Alumnae Quarterly|access-date=July 27, 2017|publisher=[[Smith College]], Office of Alumnae Relations|last1=Simpson|first1=April}}</ref> and currently lives in [[Brooklyn]], New York City.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bkmag.com/2017/03/13/brooklyn-100-influencer-kimberly-drew-metropolitan-museum-art/|title=Brooklyn 100 Influencer: Kimberly Drew, MET Museum|last=Miller|first=Rachel|date=March 13, 2017|website=Brooklyn Magazine|access-date=2017-04-11}}</ref>\n\nGrowing up, she was raised in a family of artists.<ref name=\"SSENSE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ssense.com/en-us/editorial/culture/kimberly-rose-drew|title=Kimberly Rose Drew on the Limits of Utopia|last=SSENSE|date=November 21, 2017|work=ssense|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en-us}}</ref> In 2008, Drew graduated from the [[boarding school]] [[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]] in [[Middletown, Rhode Island|Middletown]], Rhode Island.<ref name=StGeorges-NewsRoundup-2016>{{cite news|title=News Roundup: Kimberly Drew \u201908|url=http://www.stgeorges.edu/cf_news/view.cfm?newsid=226|work=[[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]]|date=July 22, 2016}}</ref> During her [[Sophomore|second year]] at [[Smith College]], Drew had an [[internship]] at [[Studio Museum in Harlem]] with [[Thelma Golden]], which influenced her later choice of concentration.<ref name=LennyLetter-Interview-2015 /> She said the experience of working in a museum informed her career path. In 2012, Drew graduated from [[Smith College]] with a B.A. in [[Art history]] and [[Africana studies]], and a concentration in [[Museology|Museum Studies]].<ref name=Smith-SAE-Spotlight-2016 />\n\n== Career ==\nIn March 2011, Drew started the [[Tumblr]] blog called \"Black Contemporary Art\" while still in college.<ref name=Smith-SAE-Spotlight-2016 /> When she began \"Black Contemporary Art,\" Drew and others would write posts about black artists who were featured on museum websites but not on Tumblr so that they \"were part of a recorded history.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/04/18/kimberly-drew-museummammy|title=Meet The Social Media Star Whose Taste The Art World Follows|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en}}</ref> As such, she aimed to help \"more marginalized people enter institutions, learn the rules, and shatter and restructure them.\"<ref name=\"Miller\"/>\n\nIn July 2015, Drew was hired as the Associate Online Community Producer at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York City.<ref name=\"Met-ArtOfSocialMedia-2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/blogs/teen-blog/2016/the-art-of-social-media|title=The Art of Social Media with Kimberly Drew|date=August 9, 2016|work=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|access-date=July 27, 2017|last1=Ambar}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Drew was invited to curate the [[White House]]'s Instagram account during the 2016 South by South Lawn festival.<ref name=\"Broadly-Feature-2016\">{{cite news|url=https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/kimberly-drew-museum-mammy-interview|title=Curator Kimberly Drew on Black Art, Social Media, and Taking Selfies in Museums|date=November 25, 2016|work=Broadly|access-date=July 27, 2017|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|last1=Agrawal|first1=Nadya}}</ref><ref name=ArtNews-SouthSouthLawn-2016>{{cite news|last1=Russeth|first1=Andrew|title=The Met's Social Medial Manager, Kimberly Drew, is on the White House's Instagram Account Today|url=http://www.artnews.com/2016/10/03/the-mets-social-media-manager-kimberly-drew-is-on-the-white-houses-instagram-account-today/|work=[[ARTnews]]|date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, Drew worked with the [[Aperture Foundation]] as a social media consultant.<ref name=\"Met-ArtOfSocialMedia-2016\" /><ref name=\"NYorker-ArtofProtest-2016\" /> [[Artsy (website)|Artsy]] included her in a roundup of art-world leaders who are \"advancing [[racial equality]] in the art world.\"\n\nIn July of 2016, Drew, along with writers Taylor Renee Aldridge and Jessica Lynne and art historian Jessica Bell Brown, organized a project called Black Art Incubator,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-mets-kimberly-drew-tells-us-the-art-world-she-wants-to-see-700547|title=Where the Met's Kimberly Drew Sees the Art World in 10 Years {{!}} artnet News|date=October 17, 2016|work=artnet News|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en-US}}</ref> a two-month long program of book exchanges, art [[critique]]s, and [[panel discussion]]s which aimed to '\u2019prioritize Black [[subjectivity]] through the use of [[social sculpture]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.recessart.org/blackartincubator/|title=BLACK ART INCUBATOR {{!}} Recess|website=www.recessart.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> \n\nDrew is currently co-authoring a book with [[Jenna Wortham]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/projects/13528952/american-women-in-art-female-artists-lorna-simpson/|title=These Women in the Arts Don't Take No for an Answer|last=Simpson|first=Koa Beck, Lorna|date=March 8, 2017|work=Vogue|access-date=2017-10-04|language=en-US}}</ref> ''The Black Futures Project,'' which will examine how creativity relates to black [[cultural identity]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/the-mets-social-media-manager-kimberly-drew-on-black-contemporary-art-public-speaking-and-more|title=This 26-Year-Old Has Already Mastered Social Media, the Met, and the Art World|last=Williamson|first=Sue|date=November 16, 2016|work=Teen Vogue|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en}}</ref> and will be published by [[Chris Jackson (publisher)|Chris Jackson]]'s One World imprint at [[Random House]] in July of 2019.<ref name=\"SSENSE\"/> Additionally, Drew will publish ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1119475558 This is What I Know About Art],'' a book for young adults'','' in June 2020 with the [[Penguin Random House|Penguin Workshop]] imprint as part of the Pocket Change Collective series<ref>https://www.teenvogue.com/story/pocket-change-collective-covers</ref>. <!--<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Black_Futures_Project.html?id=n8junAAACAAJ|title=The Black Futures Project|last=Wortham|first=Jenna|last2=Drew|first2=Kimberly|date=July 2, 2019|publisher=One World|isbn=9780399181153|language=en}}</ref>-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://blackcontemporaryart.tumblr.com Black Contemporary Art blog]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/museummammy/ @museummammy] on Instagram\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drew, Kimberly}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Smith College alumni]]\n[[Category:Women curators]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n", "name_user": "P67ii", "label": "safe", "comment": "Tweaked the occupation section to reflect that the position with the Metropolitan Museum of Art has ended, adding \"former\". If this section is supposed to only list current occupation, someone can perhaps delete it there since it's covered in the main body of the text already?", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kimberly_Drew"}
{"title_page": "Newport 41", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Sailboat class}}\n{{Infobox sailboat specifications \n|name              =Newport 41S\n|class_image       =\n|line drawing      =\n|line size         =\n|line alt          =\n|line caption      =\n|image boat        =\n|image size        =\n|image alt         =\n|image caption     =\n\n|designer          = [[C&C Design]]\n|location          = [[United States]]\n|year              = circa 1972\n|no built          = \n|design            =\n|class             =\n|brand             =\n|builder           = [[Capital Yachts]]\n|role              =\n\n|boats             =\n|crew              =\n|trapeze           =\n|draft             = {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|air draft         =\n|displacement      = {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n\n|hulls             =\n|hull type         = [[Monohull]]\n|construction      = [[Fiberglass]]\n|loa               = {{convert|41.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|loh               =\n|lwl               = {{convert|30.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|beam              = {{convert|11.25|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|hull draft        =\n|hull weight       =\n|engine            = [[Yanmar]] {{convert|35|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[diesel engine]]\n\n|appendages        =\n|keel type         = fin keel\n|ballast           = {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|rudder type       = spade-type [[rudder]]\n\n|rigs              =\n|rig type          = [[Bermuda rig]]\n|I                 = {{convert|52.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|J                 = {{convert|17.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|P                 = {{convert|44.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|E                 = {{convert|13.60|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|mast length       =\n|rig other         =\n\n|sails             =\n|sailplan          = [[Masthead sloop]]\n|sailarea main     = {{convert|299.20|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n|sailarea headsail = {{convert|442.00|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n|sailarea spin     =\n|sailarea gen      =\n|sails other       =\n|sailarea upwind   =\n|sailarea downwind =\n|sailarea total    = {{convert|741.20|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n\n|rating            =\n|d-pn              = 74.5\n|rya-pn            =\n|phrf              = 114\n\n|status            =\n|previous          =[[Redline 41]]\n|successor         =\n}}\n\nThe '''Newport 41''' is a family of [[United States|American]] [[sailboat]]s that was designed by [[C&C Design]] as [[International Offshore Rule]] (IOR) [[Sailing (sport)|racer]]-[[Cruising (maritime)|cruisers]] and first built in about 1972.<ref name=\"Data\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41s|title = Newport 41S sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://sailboatdata.com/designer/cc-design|title = C&C Design|access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190803204823/https://sailboatdata.com/designer/cc-design|archivedate = 3 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherwood\">Sherwood, Richard M.: ''A Field Guide to Sailboats of North America, Second Edition'', pages 358-359. Houghton Mifflin Company, 1994. {{ISBN|0-395-65239-1}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe design was built by [[Lindsay Plastics]] and later by [[Capital Yachts]] in [[Harbor City, California]], [[United States]]. Capital built the various models from about 1972 until the early 1990s, but it is now out of production.<ref name=\"Data\"/><ref name=\"Sherwood\"/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://sailboatdata.com/builder/capital-yachts-corp|title = Capital Yachts Corp. |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190930062158/https://sailboatdata.com/builder/capital-yachts-corp|archivedate =30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nDue to poor surviving documentation, the dates of production and new model introduction are considered to be approximate.<ref name=\"Data41\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41|title = Newport 41 sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181022203048/https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41 |archivedate =22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe Newport 41 design was based upon the 1969 [[C&C Yachts]] [[Redline 41 Mark II]]. The design went out of production in 1972 and C&C sold the molds to [[Enterprise Yachts]] who then resold them to Lindsay Plastics who built some boats, and then to Capital Yachts.<ref name=\"Data41\"/><ref name=\"Redline41MkII\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/redline-41-mkii-cc|title = Redline 41 Mk II (C&C) sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref>\n\nThe Newport 41 is a recreational [[keelboat]], built predominantly of [[fiberglass]], with [[teak]] wood trim. It has a [[masthead sloop]] rig with [[anodized]] [[aluminum]] spars, a [[raked stem]], a raised counter [[reverse transom]], a spade-type [[rudder]] controlled by a [[Ship's wheel|wheel]] and a fixed swept fin [[keel]].<ref name=\"Data\"/><ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nNewport 41S is typical of the models for interior layout. The 41S design has sleeping accommodation for seven people, with a double \"V\"-berth in the bow cabin, screened by a curtain, an \"L\"-shaped settee with a fold-down dinette table and a straight settee in the main cabin, with an optional pilot berth above, and an aft cabin with a berth on the starboard side. The [[Galley (kitchen)|galley]] is located on the port side just forward of the [[companionway]] ladder. The galley is \"U\"-shaped and is equipped with a three-burner alcohol-fired stove and a sink with manually-pumped fresh water, with manually pumped seawater and pressurized fresh water optional. A navigation station is opposite the galley, on the starboard side. The [[Head (watercraft)|head]] is located just aft of the bow cabin on the port side and includes a molded fiberglass shower.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nVentilation is provided by an opening port in the head, two translucent deck hatches and two opening ports. There are also four fixed ports.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nFor sailing, the design is equipped with a [[mainsheet traveler]] on the coach house roof. The perforated toerail can be used to mount [[sheet (sailing)|sheeting]] blocks for sail control. A [[jib]] sheet track, internally-mounted [[outhaul]], [[boom vang]] and a [[spinnaker]] were all factory options.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\n==Variants==\n;Newport 41S\n:This model was introduced in about 1972 specifically for the IOR racing rules. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|30.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted. The boat is fitted with a Japanese [[Yanmar]] [[diesel engine]] of {{convert|35|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. The fuel tank holds {{convert|35|u.s.gal}} and the fresh water tank has a capacity of {{convert|75|u.s.gal}}. Below decks headroom is {{convert|6.25|ft|cm|0|abbr=on}}. The boat has a [[Performance Handicap Racing Fleet|PHRF]] racing average handicap of 114 and a [[Portsmouth Yardstick]] of 74.5.<ref name=\"Data\"/>\n;Newport 41\n:This model was introduced in about 1977. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|30.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.42|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted.<ref name=\"Data41\"/>\n;Newport 41 Mark II\n:This model was introduced in about 1982 and incorporated a new coach house roof and rudder design. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|32.15|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted. The boat is fitted with a Universal M-40 diesel engine of {{convert|32|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. The fuel tank holds {{convert|40|u.s.gal}} and the fresh water tank has a capacity of {{convert|80|u.s.gal}}.<ref name=\"Data41\"/><ref name=\"DataMkII\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41-mk-ii|title = Newport 41 Mk II sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref>\n;Newport 41 Mark IIIA\n:This model was introduced in about 1984. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|30.50|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|16427|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted.<ref name=\"DataMkIIIA\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41-mk-iiia|title = Newport 41 Mk IIIA sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nIn a 1994 review Richard Sherwood wrote, \"perhaps the most unusual aspect of the Newport 41[S model] is the clutter of winches around the mast, all located on the cabin roof. There are five winches that almost complete a circle. These are all for halyards and vangs. All sheeting leads to the cockpit. There are two winches on the coach roof and two primary and two secondary winches at normal locations in the cockpit.\"<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nDarrell Nicholson, editor of Practical Sailor, wrote in a 2003 review, \"the N-41 makes an excellent case for the fact that a boat that was designed intelligently and built well in the first place has a good chance of standing the tests of time ... Speed and maneuverability are significant virtues in a cruising boat, and the N-41 has retained them. Sailors who enjoy racing but are less happy about the expense, discomfort, and \u201cto the edge\u201d design of today\u2019s racing boats will find the Newport 41 to their liking.\"<ref name=\"Nicholson\">{{cite web|url = https://www.practical-sailor.com/sailboat-reviews/used_sailboats/newport-41|title = Newport 41|access-date = 15 April 2020|last =Nicholson |first = Darrell  |work = Practical Sailor|date = 10 November 2003|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200419180121/https://www.practical-sailor.com/sailboat-reviews/used_sailboats/newport-41|archivedate = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of sailing boat types]]\n\n'''Similar sailboats'''\n*[[Dickerson 41]]\n*[[Lord Nelson 41]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!-- ==External links== -->\n[[Category:Keelboats]]\n[[Category:1980s sailboat type designs]]\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Sailboat class}}\n{{Infobox sailboat specifications \n|name              =Newport 41S\n|class_image       =\n|line drawing      =\n|line size         =\n|line alt          =\n|line caption      =\n|image boat        =\n|image size        =\n|image alt         =\n|image caption     =\n\n|designer          = [[C&C Design]]\n|location          = [[United States]]\n|year              = circa 1972\n|no built          = \n|design            =\n|class             =\n|brand             =\n|builder           = [[Capital Yachts]]\n|role              =\n\n|boats             =\n|crew              =\n|trapeze           =\n|draft             = {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|air draft         =\n|displacement      = {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n\n|hulls             =\n|hull type         = [[Monohull]]\n|construction      = [[Fiberglass]]\n|loa               = {{convert|41.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|loh               =\n|lwl               = {{convert|30.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|beam              = {{convert|11.25|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|hull draft        =\n|hull weight       =\n|engine            = [[Yanmar]] {{convert|35|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[diesel engine]]\n\n|appendages        =\n|keel type         = fin keel\n|ballast           = {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|rudder type       = spade-type [[rudder]]\n\n|rigs              =\n|rig type          = [[Bermuda rig]]\n|I                 = {{convert|52.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|J                 = {{convert|17.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|P                 = {{convert|44.00|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|E                 = {{convert|13.60|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|mast length       =\n|rig other         =\n\n|sails             =\n|sailplan          = [[Masthead sloop]]\n|sailarea main     = {{convert|299.20|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n|sailarea headsail = {{convert|442.00|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n|sailarea spin     =\n|sailarea gen      =\n|sails other       =\n|sailarea upwind   =\n|sailarea downwind =\n|sailarea total    = {{convert|741.20|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n\n|rating            =\n|d-pn              = 74.5\n|rya-pn            =\n|phrf              = 114\n\n|status            =\n|previous          =[[Redline 41]]\n|successor         =\n}}\n\nThe '''Newport 41''' is a family of [[United States|American]] [[sailboat]]s that was designed by [[C&C Design]] as [[International Offshore Rule]] (IOR) [[Sailing (sport)|racer]]-[[Cruising (maritime)|cruisers]] and first built in about 1972.<ref name=\"Data\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41s|title = Newport 41S sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://sailboatdata.com/designer/cc-design|title = C&C Design|access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190803204823/https://sailboatdata.com/designer/cc-design|archivedate = 3 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherwood\">Sherwood, Richard M.: ''A Field Guide to Sailboats of North America, Second Edition'', pages 358-359. Houghton Mifflin Company, 1994. {{ISBN|0-395-65239-1}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe design was built by [[Lindsay Plastics]] and later by [[Capital Yachts]] in [[Harbor City, California]], [[United States]]. Capital built the various models from about 1972 until the early 1990s, but it is now out of production.<ref name=\"Data\"/><ref name=\"Sherwood\"/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://sailboatdata.com/builder/capital-yachts-corp|title = Capital Yachts Corp. |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190930062158/https://sailboatdata.com/builder/capital-yachts-corp|archivedate =30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nDue to poor surviving documentation, the dates of production and new model introduction are considered to be approximate.<ref name=\"Data41\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41|title = Newport 41 sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181022203048/https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41 |archivedate =22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe Newport 41 design was based upon the 1969 [[C&C Yachts]] [[Redline 41 Mark II]]. The design went out of production in 1972 and C&C sold the molds to [[Enterprise Yachts]] who then resold them to Lindsay Plastics who built some boats, and then to Capital Yachts.<ref name=\"Data41\"/><ref name=\"Redline41MkII\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/redline-41-mkii-cc|title = Redline 41 Mk II (C&C) sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref>\n\nThe Newport 41 is a recreational [[keelboat]], built predominantly of [[fiberglass]], with [[teak]] wood trim. It has a [[masthead sloop]] rig with [[anodized]] [[aluminum]] spars, a [[raked stem]], a raised counter [[reverse transom]], a spade-type [[rudder]] controlled by a [[Ship's wheel|wheel]] and a fixed swept fin [[keel]].<ref name=\"Data\"/><ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nNewport 41S is typical of the models for interior layout. The 41S design has sleeping accommodation for seven people, with a double \"V\"-berth in the bow cabin, screened by a curtain, an \"L\"-shaped settee with a fold-down dinette table and a straight settee in the main cabin, with an optional pilot berth above, and an aft cabin with a berth on the starboard side. The [[Galley (kitchen)|galley]] is located on the port side just forward of the [[companionway]] ladder. The galley is \"U\"-shaped and is equipped with a three-burner alcohol-fired stove and a sink with manually-pumped fresh water, with manually pumped seawater and pressurized fresh water optional. A navigation station is opposite the galley, on the starboard side. The [[Head (watercraft)|head]] is located just aft of the bow cabin on the port side and includes a molded fiberglass shower.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nVentilation is provided by an opening port in the head, two translucent deck hatches and two opening ports. There are also four fixed ports.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nFor sailing the design is equipped with a [[mainsheet traveler]] in the coach house roof. The perforated toerail can be used to mount [[sheet (sailing)|sheeting]] blocks for sail control. A [[jib]] sheet track, internally-mounted [[outhaul]], [[boom vang]] and a [[spinnaker]] were all factory options.<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\n==Variants==\n;Newport 41S\n:This model was introduced in about 1972 specifically for the IOR racing rules. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|30.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted. The boat is fitted with a Japanese [[Yanmar]] [[diesel engine]] of {{convert|35|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. The fuel tank holds {{convert|35|u.s.gal}} and the fresh water tank has a capacity of {{convert|75|u.s.gal}}. Below decks headroom is {{convert|6.25|ft|cm|0|abbr=on}}. The boat has a [[Performance Handicap Racing Fleet|PHRF]] racing average handicap of 114 and a [[Portsmouth Yardstick]] of 74.5.<ref name=\"Data\"/>\n;Newport 41\n:This model was introduced in about 1977. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|30.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.42|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted.<ref name=\"Data41\"/>\n;Newport 41 Mark II\n:This model was introduced in about 1982 and incorporated a new coach house roof and rudder design. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|32.15|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|18000|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted. The boat is fitted with a Universal M-40 diesel engine of {{convert|32|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. The fuel tank holds {{convert|40|u.s.gal}} and the fresh water tank has a capacity of {{convert|80|u.s.gal}}.<ref name=\"Data41\"/><ref name=\"DataMkII\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41-mk-ii|title = Newport 41 Mk II sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref>\n;Newport 41 Mark IIIA\n:This model was introduced in about 1984. It has a length overall of {{convert|41.00|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, a waterline length of {{convert|30.50|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}, displaces {{convert|16427|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} and carries {{convert|8215|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} of ballast. The boat has a draft of {{convert|6.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} with the standard keel fitted.<ref name=\"DataMkIIIA\">{{cite web|url = https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/newport-41-mk-iiia|title = Newport 41 Mk IIIA sailboat |access-date = 19 April 2020|last= McArthur| first = Bruce |work = sailboatdata.com|year = 2020|archiveurl = |archivedate =}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nIn a 1994 review Richard Sherwood wrote, \"perhaps the most unusual aspect of the Newport 41[S model] is the clutter of winches around the mast, all located on the cabin roof. There are five winches that almost complete a circle. These are all for halyards and vangs. All sheeting leads to the cockpit. There are two winches on the coach roof and two primary and two secondary winches at normal locations in the cockpit.\"<ref name=\"Sherwood\"/>\n\nDarrell Nicholson, editor of Practical Sailor, wrote in a 2003 review, \"the N-41 makes an excellent case for the fact that a boat that was designed intelligently and built well in the first place has a good chance of standing the tests of time ... Speed and maneuverability are significant virtues in a cruising boat, and the N-41 has retained them. Sailors who enjoy racing but are less happy about the expense, discomfort, and \u201cto the edge\u201d design of today\u2019s racing boats will find the Newport 41 to their liking.\"<ref name=\"Nicholson\">{{cite web|url = https://www.practical-sailor.com/sailboat-reviews/used_sailboats/newport-41|title = Newport 41|access-date = 15 April 2020|last =Nicholson |first = Darrell  |work = Practical Sailor|date = 10 November 2003|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200419180121/https://www.practical-sailor.com/sailboat-reviews/used_sailboats/newport-41|archivedate = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of sailing boat types]]\n\n'''Similar sailboats'''\n*[[Dickerson 41]]\n*[[Lord Nelson 41]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!-- ==External links== -->\n[[Category:Keelboats]]\n[[Category:1980s sailboat type designs]]\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "name_user": "Ahunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDesign:wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newport_41"}
{"title_page": "\u00cdngrid Martz", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Martz|de la Vega}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Ingrid Martz\n|image         = Ingrid Martz.jpg\n|birth_name    = Ingrid Martz de la Vega\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1979|9|17}}\n|birth_place   = Mexico City, [[D.F.]], [[M\u00e9xico]]\n|years_active  = 1997-present\n|occupation    = Actress, model\n}}\n\n'''\u00cdngrid Martz de la Vega''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8i\u014b\u0261\u027ei\u00f0 \u02c8ma\u027ets}}; Mexico City, 17 September 1979) is a [[Mexican people|Mexican actress]] and model.<ref>[http://www.explored.com.ec/noticias-ecuador/el-amor-entre-karla-y-gabriel-florece-en-zacatillo-la-nueva-novela-mexicana-que-se-estrena-en-gamatv-402514.html Zacatillo, la nueva novela mexicana que se estrena en GamaTV] 14 April 2010 \"La guap\u00edsima actriz mexicana \u00cdngrid Martz da vida a la protagonista de la historia (Karla Abreu).\"</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nShe studied acting in [[Centro de Educaci\u00f3n Art\u00edstica|El Centro de Capacitaci\u00f3n Art\u00edstica de Televisa (CEA)]]. Ingrid Martz lately acted in ''La que no pod\u00eda amar'', a telenovela, as Daniella, Ana Paula's best friend and Miguel's wife.\n\nSome of credited works include ''[[Luz Clarita]]'' (1996), ''[[Mar\u00eda Isabel (1997 telenovela)|Mar\u00eda Isabel]]'' (1997), ''[[Preciosa (telenovela)|Preciosa]]'' (1998), ''[[Salud, dinero y amor]]'' (1997), ''[[Mujeres enga\u00f1adas]]'' (1999), ''[[Carita de \u00e1ngel]]'' (2000), ''[[El derecho de nacer (2001 telenovela)|El derecho de nacer]]'' (2001), ''[[El juego de la vida]]'' (2001), ''[[Amor real]]'' (2003) and ''[[Amarte es mi Pecado]]'' (2004).\n\nBesides acting in [[telenovela]]s, Ingrid has also starred in music videos and movies.\n\nIngrid, who admires actors like [[Ignacio L\u00f3pez Tarso]], [[Diana Bracho]] and [[Brad Pitt]], has said that she will never launch herself as a singer, despite several offers in the past. In 2004 she acted alongside [[B\u00e1rbara Mori]] in the hit telenovela, ''[[Rub\u00ed (2004 telenovela)|Rub\u00ed]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Telenovelas, Films, Series, Guest Appearances\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de;\n! Year|| Title ||Role||Notes\n|-\n|1996 || ''Me enamoro de ti'' with [[Fey (singer)|Fey]] || || Video clip\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1997-98|| ''[[Mar\u00eda Isabel (1997 telenovela)|Mar\u00eda Isabel]]''|| Gloria's friend||Supporting Role\n|-\n|''[[Salud, dinero y amor]]'' || Ingrid Sandoval||Supporting Role\n|-\n|1998 ||'' Preciosa'' ||Alma San Rom\u00e1n de Rivero||Supporting Role\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1999 || ''La segunda noche'' ||Director assistant ||Film\n|-\n| ''Inesperado Amor'' || || Film\n|-\n|1999 || ''[[Por tu amor]]'' || Paz Gallardo (young) || Special Appearance \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1999-00||  ''[[Mujeres enga\u00f1adas]]'' || Adriana||Supporting Role\n|-\n|''Cuento de Navidad''|| Invited in wrestling||Mini-series\n|-\n|2000-01|| ''[[Carita de \u00e1ngel]]''||Dom\u00e9nica Rossi Rivero||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2001||''[[El derecho de nacer (2001 telenovela)|El derecho de nacer]]'' ||Leonor Castro ||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2001-02 ||'' [[El juego de la vida]]''||Georgina \"Gina\" Guzm\u00e1n||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[Mujer, Casos de la Vida Real]]''|| || TV Series\n|-\n|2003|| '' [[Amor real]]''||  Pilar Piquet de M\u00e1rquez||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2004||'' [[Amarte es mi Pecado]]''|| Renata Quiroga ||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2004||'' [[Rub\u00ed (2004 telenovela)|Rub\u00ed]]''|| Lorena Trevi\u00f1o Rivero||Supporting Role\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2004 || ''Vida TV''|| ||TV Show\n|-\n|''[[Big Brother M\u00e9xico|Big Brother VIP: M\u00e9xico]]'' ||Herself/Guest || Reality Show\n|-\n| 2005|| ''[[Pablo y Andrea]]'' ||Alma Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez ||Protagonist\n|-\n|2005 ||''[[Vecinos]]''  ||Samantha Rosas || TV Series\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2006 ||''[[RBD: La Familia]]'' || || TV Series\n|-\n| ''Asi del precipicio'' || Hanna|| Film\n|-\n| ''[[Heridas de amor]]''  || Renata San Llorente de Arag\u00f3n ||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2007-08||''[[Tormenta en el para\u00edso]]''  ||Karina Rosenberg/Valeria Ross \"Sirenita\"||Co-protagonist\n|-\n|2009|| ''Tiempo Final 3'' ||Adriana || TV Series\n|-\n|2010||''[[Zacatillo, un lugar en tu coraz\u00f3n]]''  ||Karla Abreu Campos de Z\u00e1rate ||Protagonist\n|-\n|2011-12||''[[La que no pod\u00eda amar]]'' ||Daniela \"Dany\" Guti\u00e9rrez ||Co-protagonist\n|-\n|2013||''[[Coraz\u00f3n Indomable]] ''|| Doris Montenegro ||Antagonist\n|-\n|2013-14 || ''[[Qu\u00e9 pobres tan ricos]]''|| Minerva Fontanet Blanco ex de Ruizpalacios||Main Antagonist\n|-\n|2015-16 || ''[[Antes muerta que Lichita]]''|| Luciana de Toledo y Mondrag\u00f3n || Protagonist/Antagonist\n|-\n|2017 || ''[[Divina, est\u00e1 en tu coraz\u00f3n]]''|| Brisa || Main Antagonist\n|-\n|2017 || ''[[3 familias]]''|| Bela Barroso || Protagonist\n|}\n\n===Theater===\n*''Busco al hombre de mi vida, marido ya tuve''\n*''Chicas Cat\u00f3licas''\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===[[Premios TVyNovelas]]===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de;\n! Year|| Category ||Telenovela||Result\n|-\n|2007 ||Best Co-star Actress ||''[[Heridas de amor]]''||{{nom}}\n|-\n|2017 ||Best Female Villain ||\"[[Antes muerta que Lichita]]\"||{{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0554456}}\n*[http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/artistas/368346.html Ingrid Martz] at the Esmas\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martz, Ingrid}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican telenovela actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican television actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican film actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican female models]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of German descent]]\n[[Category:People from Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Martz|de la Vega}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Ingrid Martz\n|birth_name    = Ingrid Martz de la Vega\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1979|9|17}}\n|birth_place   = Mexico City, [[D.F.]], [[M\u00e9xico]]\n|years_active  = 1997-present\n|occupation    = Actress, model\n}}\n\n'''\u00cdngrid Martz de la Vega''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8i\u014b\u0261\u027ei\u00f0 \u02c8ma\u027ets}}; Mexico City, 17 September 1979) is a [[Mexican people|Mexican actress]] and model.<ref>[http://www.explored.com.ec/noticias-ecuador/el-amor-entre-karla-y-gabriel-florece-en-zacatillo-la-nueva-novela-mexicana-que-se-estrena-en-gamatv-402514.html Zacatillo, la nueva novela mexicana que se estrena en GamaTV] 14 April 2010 \"La guap\u00edsima actriz mexicana \u00cdngrid Martz da vida a la protagonista de la historia (Karla Abreu).\"</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nShe studied acting in [[Centro de Educaci\u00f3n Art\u00edstica|El Centro de Capacitaci\u00f3n Art\u00edstica de Televisa (CEA)]]. Ingrid Martz lately acted in ''La que no pod\u00eda amar'', a telenovela, as Daniella, Ana Paula's best friend and Miguel's wife.\n\nSome of credited works include ''[[Luz Clarita]]'' (1996), ''[[Mar\u00eda Isabel (1997 telenovela)|Mar\u00eda Isabel]]'' (1997), ''[[Preciosa (telenovela)|Preciosa]]'' (1998), ''[[Salud, dinero y amor]]'' (1997), ''[[Mujeres enga\u00f1adas]]'' (1999), ''[[Carita de \u00e1ngel]]'' (2000), ''[[El derecho de nacer (2001 telenovela)|El derecho de nacer]]'' (2001), ''[[El juego de la vida]]'' (2001), ''[[Amor real]]'' (2003) and ''[[Amarte es mi Pecado]]'' (2004).\n\nBesides acting in [[telenovela]]s, Ingrid has also starred in music videos and movies.\n\nIngrid, who admires actors like [[Ignacio L\u00f3pez Tarso]], [[Diana Bracho]] and [[Brad Pitt]], has said that she will never launch herself as a singer, despite several offers in the past. In 2004 she acted alongside [[B\u00e1rbara Mori]] in the hit telenovela, ''[[Rub\u00ed (2004 telenovela)|Rub\u00ed]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Telenovelas, Films, Series, Guest Appearances\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de;\n! Year|| Title ||Role||Notes\n|-\n|1996 || ''Me enamoro de ti'' with [[Fey (singer)|Fey]] || || Video clip\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1997-98|| ''[[Mar\u00eda Isabel (1997 telenovela)|Mar\u00eda Isabel]]''|| Gloria's friend||Supporting Role\n|-\n|''[[Salud, dinero y amor]]'' || Ingrid Sandoval||Supporting Role\n|-\n|1998 ||'' Preciosa'' ||Alma San Rom\u00e1n de Rivero||Supporting Role\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1999 || ''La segunda noche'' ||Director assistant ||Film\n|-\n| ''Inesperado Amor'' || || Film\n|-\n|1999 || ''[[Por tu amor]]'' || Paz Gallardo (young) || Special Appearance \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1999-00||  ''[[Mujeres enga\u00f1adas]]'' || Adriana||Supporting Role\n|-\n|''Cuento de Navidad''|| Invited in wrestling||Mini-series\n|-\n|2000-01|| ''[[Carita de \u00e1ngel]]''||Dom\u00e9nica Rossi Rivero||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2001||''[[El derecho de nacer (2001 telenovela)|El derecho de nacer]]'' ||Leonor Castro ||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2001-02 ||'' [[El juego de la vida]]''||Georgina \"Gina\" Guzm\u00e1n||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[Mujer, Casos de la Vida Real]]''|| || TV Series\n|-\n|2003|| '' [[Amor real]]''||  Pilar Piquet de M\u00e1rquez||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2004||'' [[Amarte es mi Pecado]]''|| Renata Quiroga ||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2004||'' [[Rub\u00ed (2004 telenovela)|Rub\u00ed]]''|| Lorena Trevi\u00f1o Rivero||Supporting Role\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2004 || ''Vida TV''|| ||TV Show\n|-\n|''[[Big Brother M\u00e9xico|Big Brother VIP: M\u00e9xico]]'' ||Herself/Guest || Reality Show\n|-\n| 2005|| ''[[Pablo y Andrea]]'' ||Alma Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez ||Protagonist\n|-\n|2005 ||''[[Vecinos]]''  ||Samantha Rosas || TV Series\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2006 ||''[[RBD: La Familia]]'' || || TV Series\n|-\n| ''Asi del precipicio'' || Hanna|| Film\n|-\n| ''[[Heridas de amor]]''  || Renata San Llorente de Arag\u00f3n ||Supporting Role\n|-\n|2007-08||''[[Tormenta en el para\u00edso]]''  ||Karina Rosenberg/Valeria Ross \"Sirenita\"||Co-protagonist\n|-\n|2009|| ''Tiempo Final 3'' ||Adriana || TV Series\n|-\n|2010||''[[Zacatillo, un lugar en tu coraz\u00f3n]]''  ||Karla Abreu Campos de Z\u00e1rate ||Protagonist\n|-\n|2011-12||''[[La que no pod\u00eda amar]]'' ||Daniela \"Dany\" Guti\u00e9rrez ||Co-protagonist\n|-\n|2013||''[[Coraz\u00f3n Indomable]] ''|| Doris Montenegro ||Antagonist\n|-\n|2013-14 || ''[[Qu\u00e9 pobres tan ricos]]''|| Minerva Fontanet Blanco ex de Ruizpalacios||Main Antagonist\n|-\n|2015-16 || ''[[Antes muerta que Lichita]]''|| Luciana de Toledo y Mondrag\u00f3n || Protagonist/Antagonist\n|-\n|2017 || ''[[Divina, est\u00e1 en tu coraz\u00f3n]]''|| Brisa || Main Antagonist\n|-\n|2017 || ''[[3 familias]]''|| Bela Barroso || Protagonist\n|}\n\n===Theater===\n*''Busco al hombre de mi vida, marido ya tuve''\n*''Chicas Cat\u00f3licas''\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===[[Premios TVyNovelas]]===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de;\n! Year|| Category ||Telenovela||Result\n|-\n|2007 ||Best Co-star Actress ||''[[Heridas de amor]]''||{{nom}}\n|-\n|2017 ||Best Female Villain ||\"[[Antes muerta que Lichita]]\"||{{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0554456}}\n*[http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/artistas/368346.html Ingrid Martz] at the Esmas\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martz, Ingrid}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican telenovela actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican television actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican film actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Mexican female models]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of German descent]]\n[[Category:People from Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "103.4.17.195", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 951942977 byBradford(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%8Dngrid_Martz"}
{"title_page": "Farleigh Wallop", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country =                     England\n|official_name =               Farleigh Wallop\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.2166|-1.1104|display=inline,title}}\n| population = \n| population_ref =  \n|shire_district =              [[Basingstoke and Deane]]\n|shire_county =                [[Hampshire]]\n|region =                      South East England\n|constituency_westminster =    [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Basingstoke]]\n|post_town =                   BASINGSTOKE\n|postcode_area =               RG\n|postcode_district =           RG25\n|dial_code =                   01256\n|os_grid_reference =           \n|website =                     \n}}\n\n'''Farleigh Wallop''' is a small village and [[civil parish]] in [[Hampshire]], England, approximately {{convert|4.7|mi|km}} south of [[Basingstoke]] on the slopes of [[Farleigh Hill]] (208 m). The parish includes about {{convert|1725|acre|km2}}.\n\nSince 1486, Farleigh Wallop has been the home of the Wallop family, including [[John Wallop]], [[Henry Wallop]], and [[Gerard Wallop, 9th Earl of Portsmouth]], whose seat, [[Farleigh House (Hampshire)|Farleigh House]], is in the village.<ref>{{cite web|title=Farleigh House|url=http://www.ngs.org.uk/gardens/gardenfinder/garden.aspx?id=18968|publisher=National Garden Society|access-date=2013-10-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029220809/http://www.ngs.org.uk/gardens/gardenfinder/garden.aspx?id=18968|archive-date=2013-10-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Farleigh Wallop}}\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42001  \"Parishes: Farleigh Wallop\", A History of the County of Hampshire: Volume 3 (1908), pp. 364-366, British History Online]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070808034724/http://www3.hants.gov.uk/localpages/north-east/basingstoke/farleigh-wallop.htm  Hampshire County Council page]\n\n{{Basingstoke and Deane}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Basingstoke and Deane]]\n[[Category:Villages in Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country =                     England\n|official_name =               Farleigh Wallop\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.2166|-1.1104|display=inline,title}}\n| population = \n| population_ref =  \n|shire_district =              [[Basingstoke and Deane]]\n|shire_county =                [[Hampshire]]\n|region =                      South East England\n|constituency_westminster =    [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Basingstoke]]\n|post_town =                   BASINGSTOKE\n|postcode_area =               RG\n|postcode_district =           RG25 2\n|dial_code =                   01256\n|os_grid_reference =           \n|website =                     \n}}\n\n'''Farleigh Wallop''' is a small village and [[civil parish]] in [[Hampshire]], England, approximately {{convert|4.7|mi|km}} south of [[Basingstoke]] on the slopes of [[Farleigh Hill]] (208 m). The parish includes about {{convert|1725|acre|km2}}.\n\nSince 1486, Farleigh Wallop has been the home of the Wallop family, including [[John Wallop]], [[Henry Wallop]], and [[Gerard Wallop, 9th Earl of Portsmouth]], whose seat, [[Farleigh House (Hampshire)|Farleigh House]], is in the village.<ref>{{cite web|title=Farleigh House|url=http://www.ngs.org.uk/gardens/gardenfinder/garden.aspx?id=18968|publisher=National Garden Society|access-date=2013-10-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029220809/http://www.ngs.org.uk/gardens/gardenfinder/garden.aspx?id=18968|archive-date=2013-10-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Farleigh Wallop}}\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42001  \"Parishes: Farleigh Wallop\", A History of the County of Hampshire: Volume 3 (1908), pp. 364-366, British History Online]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070808034724/http://www3.hants.gov.uk/localpages/north-east/basingstoke/farleigh-wallop.htm  Hampshire County Council page]\n\n{{Basingstoke and Deane}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Basingstoke and Deane]]\n[[Category:Villages in Hampshire]]\n", "name_user": "AJP", "label": "safe", "comment": "postcode district only", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Farleigh_Wallop"}
{"title_page": "My Big Big Friend", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = My Big Big Friend\n| show_name_2              = Meu Amig\u00e3oz\u00e3o (Brazil)\n| image                    =\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| creator                  = Andr\u00e9s Lieban<br />Claudia Koogan Breitman\n| voices                   = See [[#Cast|below]]\n| executive_producer       = Andr\u00e9 Breitman<br />Ira Levy<br />Peter Williamson\n| country                  = [[Canada]]<br />[[Brazil]]\n| language                 = English<br />Portuguese\n| producer                 = Stephanie Betts<br />Meghan Read\n| director                 = Andr\u00e9s Lieban\n| network                  = [[Discovery Kids]] ([[Latin America]] and [[Brazil]])<br>[[Treehouse TV]] ([[Canada]])\n| num_seasons              = 2\n| num_episodes             = 52\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[SDTV]]) (Season 1)<br>[[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]]) (Season 2)\n| first_aired              = '''Brazil:''' {{start date|2010|8|9}} - 2012<br>'''Canada:''' {{start date|2011|8|20}}-2012\n}}\n\n'''''My Big Big Friend''''' (pt: '''Meu Amig\u00e3oz\u00e3o''') is a Canadian-Brazilian flash-animated children's television series created by Canadian and Brazilian Andr\u00e9s Lieban and Claudian Koogan Breitman, co-produced by Brazilian studio 2D Lab and the Canadian company [[Breakthrough Entertainment|Breakthrough Animation]]. \n\nIt had its first showing on August 9, 2010 on [[Discovery Kids Latin America]] and on May 9, 2011 on TV Brazil. It also premiered in [[Canada]] on [[Treehouse TV]] on August 20, 2011. It was financed with the laws of federal tax incentives, the Procult (BNDES) and the Audiovisual Sector Fund - FSA.\n\nThe show centers around the friendships of three children, Yuri, Lili and Matt, each of whom has a \"Big Big Friend\" who is invisible to adults and other children but seen by all three friends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/pop-arte/noticia/2010/08/animacao-meu-amigaozao-mostra-amizade-de-criancas-e-superanimais.html|title=\"Anima\u00e7\u00e3o \u2018Meu amig\u00e3oZ\u00e3o\u2019 mostra amizade de crian\u00e7as e \u2018superanimais\u2019\". ''G1'', 9 de agosto de 2010}}</ref>\n\nThis TV show is flash-animated with [[Toon Boom Animation|Toon Boom Harmony]].\n\n==Characters==\n*'''Yuri''' - Yuri is 5 years old.  He is smart, independent and happy, and has a very fertile imagination.  He is an only child, and as a result is sometimes lonely, and can be a little selfish.\n*'''Lili''' - Lili is almost 6 years old, very determined and loyal, and often speaks before she thinks.  She is the oldest of four children, and often tries to help take care of her 3 baby brothers; this has given her a tendency towards bossiness, which her friends do not always like, especially when she tries to take control of their games.\n*'''Matt''' - Matt is 7 years old, loves to play sports, and is very energetic in everything he does. He is very curious, full of ideas and opinions, and very mischievous, which means he is often getting into trouble.  He has an older sister named Nina who often teases him.\n\n===Big Friends===\n*'''Golias''' - Golias, Yuri's Big Big Friend, is a large, round, blue [[elephant]]. Golias is affectionate, likes to act, dress up, try new things and play outdoors. He is also very timid, and gnashes his teeth in fear if the lights are out. He loves to give Yuri trunk rides, and is quite sad if he ever feels left out. In Spanish he is called Goliat.\n*'''Nessa''' - Nessa is Lili's Big Big Friend.  She is a pink [[giraffe]] who can make friends with anyone, and is optimistic and cheerful. Nessa also lets Lili ride on her neck. She is agreeable and mediates conflicts.\n*'''Bongo''' - Matt's Big Big Friend is named Bongo; he is a green [[Kangaroo]]. Like Matt, he is athletic, energetic and constantly jumping.  He has a great sense of humor and an infectious, uncontrollable laugh.  Bongo is afraid of being ignored and likes attention. Bongo is also very fearful. He has a pouch that Matt rides in despite the fact he is a male kangaroo. His pouch is apparently in more than one spot, since Bongo can be seen pulling things out or putting things into different pouches in various locations, such as, up by his neck, down at his sides (almost like pockets).\n\n==Cast==\n===Canada===\n* Yuri - [[Nissae Isen]]\n* Matt - [[Gage Munroe]]\n* Lili - [[Addison Holley]]\n* Golias - [[Keanu Reeves]]\n* Bongo - [[Rick Miller (comedian)|Rick Miller]]\n* Nessa - [[Tajja Isen]]\n\n===Brazil===\n* Yuri - [[Fernanda Ribeiro (voice actor)|Fernanda Ribeiro]]\n* Matt - [[Eduardo Drummond]]\n* Lili - [[Anna Rita Cerqueira]]\n* Golias - [[M\u00e1rcio Sim\u00f5es]]\n* Bongo - [[S\u00e9rgio Stern]]\n* Nessa - [[Lina Mendes]]\n\n==Episodes==\n{{expand section|date=December 2016}}\n===Season 1===\n*Episode 1: Brickle Pickle, All the way up\n*Episode 2: Hippo-licious/Clowning Around \n*Episode 3: Air Buddies/The Sneakers\n\n<br />\n\n*Episode 4: Skipping Stones/No Kid is an Island \n*Episode 5: Show and Tell/Perfect Princess \n*Episode 6: Count Glerm/Hair Brained Idea\n*Episode 12: Fort Messy, Beach Blast\n*Episode 13: Finders Keepers\n*Episode 14: Music Man, Dream On\n*Episode 15: King of the Monkeys\n*Episode 16: It's My Party, Doggy Duty\n<ref name=11-16>https://web.archive.org/web/20140214065545/http://www.rogersondemand.com/OnDemand/Show/my_big_big_friend?lang=en\nEP 15 King of the Monkeys Aired on 01/13/14\nEP 14 Music Man, Dream On Aired on 01/13/14\nEP 16 It's My Party, Doggy Duty Aired on 01/13/14\nEP 13 Finders Keepers Aired on 12/11/13\nEP 12 Fort Messy, Beach Blast Aired on 12/11/13\nEP 11 Faeries of the Forest Aired on 12/11/13</ref>\n*17-19 TBA\n*Episode 20: Lili Bee Flower Power\n*Episode 21: No My Game, Manly Matt\n*Episode 22: Stickers, Matt's Fun Park\n*Episode 23: Big and Small, Super Lilly, Valentine's Day{{fa